<DOC><DOCNO> AP900227-0058 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-90 0830EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     02-27 0211</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Boat People,0215</SECOND><HEAD>12th Group of Boat People Repatriated Voluntarily</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A group of Vietnamese boat people returnedvoluntarily to their Communist homeland today, the 12th group to doso since the program began early last year.   The group of 115 Vietnamese brought to 1,284 the number who havereturned under the U.N. program. Nearly 1,600 more have asked toleave the overcrowded detention centers of Hong Kong and go home.   About 44,000 Vietnamese have arrived in this British colonysince June 1988, when the government decided to classify arrivingboat people as illegal immigrants unless they can prove they fledpersecution.   Only about 10 percent will be granted refugee status. The restface repatriation against their will, unless they volunteer to gohome.   The United Nations provides Vietnamese who return voluntarilywith up to $50 in cash and a monthly allowance of $30 for one year.   The voluntary repatriation program is expected to speed up nowthat Hanoi has agreed to accept 1,000 returning boat people eachmonth.   The repatriation of boat people against their will remains onhold after an initial departure of 51 Vietnamese in December. Hanoihas expressed reservations about the program because of criticismfrom the United States and human rights organizations.</TEXT></DOC>